    <h1>LG Dryer Overheating? Professional Repair in Los Angeles</h1>
    <p>When your LG dryer gets dangerously hot to the touch or your clothes come out scorched, something is seriously wrong with the temperature regulation system. Overheating isn't just an inconvenience — it's a fire hazard that our technicians treat as an urgent repair across Los Angeles.</p>
<h2>Common Causes of LG Dryer Overheating</h2>
<p>The number one cause of overheating in LG dryers is restricted airflow from a clogged exhaust vent. Our technicians find this in about 70% of overheating calls — lint accumulates in the vent line over years until airflow drops so low that heat can't escape the drum. The dryer's internal temperature climbs past safe operating limits, triggering safety shutoffs or worse, damaging internal components. The cycling thermostat is designed to regulate temperature by turning the heating element on and off throughout the cycle. When it fails, the element runs continuously and the dryer gets dangerously hot. We also see failed felt seals around the drum allowing hot air to escape into the cabinet, making the exterior feel like a radiator.</p>
<h3>Blocked Exhaust Vent Issues</h3>
<p>A partially blocked vent is actually more dangerous than a fully blocked one. Full blockages trigger the thermal fuse immediately, shutting down heat. Partial blockages let the dryer keep heating but restrict enough airflow to push temperatures past safe limits without tripping the fuse right away. Our techs check vent airflow at the exterior hood first — if you can barely feel air coming out while the dryer runs, the vent needs professional cleaning.</p>
<h3>Failed Cycling Thermostat</h3>
<p>The cycling thermostat monitors drum temperature and cycles the heating element to maintain consistent heat. When it sticks in the closed position, the element stays on indefinitely. Our technicians test thermostat continuity at different temperatures to determine if it's opening and closing properly. A $15 part can prevent hundreds in damage if caught early.</p>
<h2>Warning Signs Your LG Dryer is Overheating</h2>
<p>Don't wait for scorched clothes to address overheating. The early signs are subtle but distinctive. The dryer exterior feels unusually hot — it should be warm during operation but never too hot to touch comfortably. Your laundry room feels noticeably hotter than usual when the dryer runs. Clothes come out extremely hot or with a slight burning smell. The dryer shuts off mid-cycle with error codes like D80, D90, or D95, which indicate restricted airflow. Our techs also look for discolored or yellowing lint in the screen, which means lint is being exposed to excessive heat inside the machine.</p>
<h3>When to Stop Using Your Dryer Immediately</h3>
<p>If you smell burning plastic or see scorch marks on clothing, shut off the dryer and unplug it immediately. These signs mean internal temperatures have exceeded safe limits and continued operation risks fire. Call us for same-day emergency service rather than trying to diagnose the problem yourself.</p>
<h3>Error Codes Related to Overheating</h3>
<p>LG dryers display specific codes when overheating conditions are detected. The D80 through D95 codes indicate progressively worse airflow restriction. Our technicians see these codes constantly — they're your dryer telling you the vent system needs attention before the thermal fuse blows or worse.</p>
<h2>How Our Technicians Diagnose Overheating Problems</h2>
<p>Our diagnostic process starts with measuring exhaust vent airflow at the exterior hood using an anemometer. Proper airflow should register above 500 feet per minute at the outlet. Next, we check internal component temperatures during a running cycle using infrared thermometers — the heating element housing shouldn't exceed 250°F during normal operation. We test the cycling thermostat, high-limit thermostat, and thermal fuse for proper continuity values. Our techs also inspect the heating element itself for shorts to ground, which can cause it to run at higher-than-designed wattage.</p>
<h3>Complete Vent System Inspection</h3>
<p>We trace the entire vent path from the dryer connection to the exterior hood, checking for crushed sections, excessive length, or too many elbows that restrict airflow. Many homes in Los Angeles have vents routed through walls and attics that accumulate lint in hidden bends. Our technicians use rotary brush systems to clean the full length of the vent.</p>
<h3>Component Testing Sequence</h3>
<p>Our techs follow a specific testing order: thermal fuse first, then cycling thermostat, high-limit thermostat, and finally the heating element. This sequence quickly isolates the failed component without unnecessary disassembly.</p>
<h2>Repairs That Fix LG Dryer Overheating</h2>
<p>The fix depends entirely on the root cause. Professional vent cleaning solves most overheating issues immediately — our techs clear the entire vent run and verify proper airflow before leaving. If the cycling thermostat has failed, we replace it with a genuine LG part and test the heating element to ensure it cycles properly. Blown thermal fuses get replaced, but we always identify why the fuse blew in the first place. Simply replacing a thermal fuse without fixing the underlying airflow problem means it'll blow again within weeks. For heating element shorts, we install a new OEM element and verify proper wattage draw.</p>
<h3>Thermal Fuse Replacement</h3>
<p>A blown thermal fuse is often the result of overheating, not the cause. Our technicians replace the fuse and then investigate what caused the excessive temperature — usually a blocked vent or failed thermostat. Replacing just the fuse without fixing the root cause is a temporary fix at best.</p>
<h3>Vent System Upgrades</h3>
<p>Homes with flexible plastic or foil vent ducting get a strong recommendation from our techs to upgrade to rigid aluminum. Flexible ducting traps lint in its ridges and restricts airflow far more than smooth rigid pipe. The upgrade costs relatively little and dramatically reduces overheating risk.</p>
<h2>Preventing LG Dryer Overheating</h2>
<p>Clean your lint screen after every single load — this is non-negotiable. Schedule professional vent cleaning annually, or every six months if you run heavy loads daily. Check the exterior vent hood monthly to make sure the flap opens freely and nothing is blocking it. Don't overload your dryer — stuffed loads restrict internal airflow and force the heating system to work harder. Our technicians also recommend pulling the dryer out periodically to check the transition hose between the dryer and wall connection for kinks or lint buildup.</p>
<h3>Maintenance Schedule</h3>
<p>Our techs recommend annual professional vent cleaning for most households. Families running more than one load daily should consider semi-annual cleaning. We offer maintenance visits that include vent cleaning, internal lint removal, and component inspection to catch overheating risks before they become emergencies.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>Why is my LG dryer getting too hot?</h3>
<p>The most common cause is a clogged exhaust vent restricting airflow, which traps heat inside the drum. Failed cycling thermostats, damaged felt seals, and shorted heating elements can also cause overheating. Our technicians diagnose the exact cause and fix it same-day — don't keep running an overheating dryer as it's a fire hazard.</p>
<h3>What do LG dryer error codes D80, D90, and D95 mean?</h3>
<p>These codes indicate restricted exhaust airflow at increasing severity levels. D80 means 80% blockage, D90 means 90%, and D95 means the vent is nearly completely blocked. Your dryer is overheating because heat can't escape through the vent. Call us for professional vent cleaning — these codes won't clear until airflow is restored to proper levels.</p>
<h3>Is it dangerous to use an overheating dryer?</h3>
<p>Yes, absolutely. An overheating dryer is a fire hazard. Dryer fires cause thousands of house fires annually, and restricted venting is the leading cause. If your dryer is getting excessively hot, producing burning smells, or scorching clothes, stop using it immediately and call for professional repair.</p>
<h3>How much does it cost to fix an overheating LG dryer?</h3>
<p>Most overheating repairs run $100-250 depending on the cause. Professional vent cleaning is on the lower end, while thermostat or heating element replacement costs more. We charge a $65 diagnostic fee that's waived when you proceed with the repair. Our techs give you exact pricing before starting any work.</p>
<h3>How often should I clean my dryer vent to prevent overheating?</h3>
<p>We recommend professional vent cleaning at least once a year for most households. If you do laundry daily or have a long vent run through walls or attic, clean it every six months. Always clean the lint screen after every load, and check the exterior vent hood monthly to ensure proper airflow.</p>
